      "1} |A_j| = sum_{i ∈ B} d_i`. \n\nThus `sum_{i ∈ B} d_i = (2n + 1)(2n)`, and since `d_i ≥ 2`, `2 |B| ≤ (2n + 1)(2n)`, so `|B| ≤ (2n + 1)(2n)/2 = (4n² + 2n)/2 = 2n² + n`.\n\nBut perhaps another bound? \n\nAlternatively, we have:\n`sum_{j < k} |A_j ∩ A_k| = sum_{i ∈ B} (d_i choose 2)` because each `i` appearing in `d_i` sets contributes `d_i(d_i - 1)/2` to the LHS.\n\nIn our case, `sum_{j < k} |A_j ∩ A_k| = (2n + 1 choose 2) * 1 = (2n + 1)(2n)/2 = n(2n + 1)`.\n\nHence, `sum_{i ∈ B} (d_i choose 2) = n(2n + 1)`.\n\nBut since `d_i ≥ 2`, `(d_i choose 2) ≥ d_i - 1` (since `(d choose 2) = d(d - 1)/2 ≥ d - 1` when `d ≥ 2`).\n\nThus, `n(2n + 1) ≥ sum_{i ∈ B} (d_i - 1) = sum d_i - |B| = (2n + 1)(2n) - |B|`.\n\nTherefore, `n(2n + 1) ≥ (2n + 1)(2n) - |B|`, which gives `|B| ≥ (2n + 1)(2n) - n(2n + 1) = (2n + 1)(2n - n) = n(2n + 1)`.\n\nBut earlier we",
